<div class="mod-prose">

  <p>You must take care not to reveal any sensitive data about an individual when carrying out user research.</p>

  <p>Sensitive data is any information that could cause the participant embarrassment or distress and which they can reasonably expect to remain private. This includes:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>age</li>
    <li>marital status</li>
    <li>racial or ethnic origin</li>
    <li>nationality</li>
    <li>physical or mental health or condition, including disability status</li>
    <li>sexual life</li>
    <li>biometrics and genetics</li>
    <li>photographs, videos or sound recordings in which individuals can be identified</li>
    <li>any data collected where a guarantee of confidentiality was given</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Sensitive data also covers things like:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>political opinions</li>
    <li>religious or similar beliefs</li>
    <li>benefit claims history or entitlement</li>
    <li>membership of trade unions</li>
    <li>commission or alleged commission of an offence</li>
    <li>cause of death, where this is not a matter of public record</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="non-sensitive-data">Non-sensitive data</h2>

  <p>Some personal data items are not considered sensitive when captured on their own. These include a participantâ€™s:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>sex</li>
    <li>rank or grade</li>
    <li>full-time or part-time working status</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="surveys-and-questionnaires">Surveys and questionnaires</h2>

  <p>Check that you are only collecting the data that you need to answer your research questions.</p>

  <p>Unless it is essential to your research, consider not collecting information on protected characteristics, including:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>gender</li>
    <li>age</li>
    <li>disability status</li>
    <li>sexuality</li>
    <li>education background</li>
    <li>ethnicity</li>
    <li>nationality</li>
    <li>marital status</li>
    <li>caring responsibilities</li>
  </ul>

</div>

